and the powers that be decide...

7
00:00:49,800 --> 00:00:52,736
...whether you're destined
for greatness or mediocrity.

8
00:00:53,737 --> 00:00:55,467
I know what you're thinking.

9
00:00:55,539 --> 00:00:57,007
Do I really belong here?

10
00:00:57,774 --> 00:00:59,970
Probably not. But don't give in.

11
00:01:00,043 --> 00:01:01,067
Don't give up.

12
00:01:01,144 --> 00:01:02,908
Arise, fair Harvard.

13
00:01:03,046 --> 00:01:04,036
Arise.

14
00:01:04,248 --> 00:01:06,308
You too can rule the world.

15
00:01:06,950 --> 00:01:09,476
You just have to crush everyone else first.

16
00:01:10,287 --> 00:01:12,415
A little crushing music, Maestro.

17
00:01:48,125 --> 00:01:49,684
All right guys, let's go!

18
00:01:57,067 --> 00:01:59,161
You can do it. Keep going!

19
00:02:07,077 --> 00:02:09,103
Keep up the pace! Nice and neat!

20
00:02:12,516 --> 00:02:13,882
Ignore him!

21
00:02:15,319 --> 00:02:16,787
Move it! Let's go!

22
00:02:20,991 --> 00:02:22,653
Very funny, Monty!

23
00:02:29,933 --> 00:02:31,993
Now, here's something to crow about.

24
00:02:32,302 --> 00:02:33,964
I've got a great cock, don't I?
 
25
00:02:34,037 --> 00:02:36,871
You see, last night,
a Radcliffe sophomore saw a ghost...

26
00:02:36,940 --> 00:02:40,604
...looking remarkably like Walt Whitman
in Widener Library.

27
00:02:41,345 --> 00:02:44,247
America's greatest poet
haunting the stacks, eh.

28
00:02:44,581 --> 00:02:48,518
The Cliffie is undergoing intense debriefing
by the English department.

29
00:02:48,785 --> 00:02:49,912
They better hurry.

30
00:02:49,986 --> 00:02:53,855
Weather tells us that 10 inches of
the white shroud is scheduled for tonight.

31
00:02:54,358 --> 00:02:55,724
I'm Everett Calloway.

32
00:02:55,792 --> 00:02:57,693
Now you hear me. Now you....

33
00:02:59,363 --> 00:03:02,026
Your father called
and wants you to call him back.

34
00:03:02,099 --> 00:03:03,499
What's up with Father?

35
00:03:03,567 --> 00:03:05,365
Marrying my sister, perhaps.

36
00:03:06,236 --> 00:03:08,967
He mumbled something
about your being overdrawn...

37
00:03:09,306 --> 00:03:10,239
again!

38
00:03:11,441 --> 00:03:14,878
I thought he was a patriot.
Doesn't he believe in deficit spending.

39
00:03:16,580 --> 00:03:17,980
Lord Montague!

40
00:03:18,582 --> 00:03:21,609
You're looking very grim and formal
this morning.

41
00:03:22,018 --> 00:03:23,748
You trying to pass for a Yalie?

42
00:03:24,454 --> 00:03:26,320
I've got a meeting with Pitkannan.

43
00:03:26,757 --> 00:03:28,988
Oh, no. Not about the thesis!

44
00:03:29,860 --> 00:03:32,125
- Feeling confident?
- Feeling nauseous.

45
00:03:32,195 --> 00:03:33,424
This one here.

46
00:03:33,964 --> 00:03:35,125
Oh, God.

47
00:03:36,867 --> 00:03:39,098
I know her. I've been with her.

48
00:03:39,970 --> 00:03:41,871
First paragraph, Mr. Kessler.

49
00:03:42,606 --> 00:03:44,006
Let's hear it.

50
00:03:45,642 --> 00:03:46,632
''Chapter 1.''

51
00:03:46,710 --> 00:03:47,700
From memory.

52
00:03:47,778 --> 00:03:48,802
Yes, sir!

53
00:03:48,912 --> 00:03:51,381
I don't know whether that denotes
hard work, or...

54
00:03:51,615 --> 00:03:53,106
...unseemly vanity.

55
00:03:53,784 --> 00:03:54,911
Stand up!

56
00:03:56,486 --> 00:03:57,476
Stand up?

57
00:03:57,621 --> 00:03:59,749
I like a substantial target.

58
00:04:06,396 --> 00:04:07,364
''Chapter 1.

59
00:04:08,732 --> 00:04:10,291
''The Bottomless Well of Need.

60
00:04:11,034 --> 00:04:14,732
''The noble and ambitious assumption
of the government of the United States...

61
00:04:14,971 --> 00:04:18,203
''...is that the needs of a diverse population
can be fulfilled.

62
00:04:18,775 --> 00:04:22,837
''The dream of a melting pot has become
a cauldron of inflexible minorities...

63
00:04:23,847 --> 00:04:25,975
''...and the hopelessly unemployable.

64
00:04:26,216 --> 00:04:29,709
''The solution is to leave the complexities
of modern government...

65
00:04:29,886 --> 00:04:31,548
''...to the political expert.

66
00:04:32,856 --> 00:04:36,156
''And to rethink our naive faith
in the wisdom of the people.''

67
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:38,460
A good beginning.

68
00:04:39,196 --> 00:04:40,459
Leave your chapter.

69
00:04:40,530 --> 00:04:43,898
And if the rest of your thesis is
as intelligent as you are...

70
00:04:44,334 --> 00:04:47,896
...you are certain to graduate
summa cum laude...

71
00:04:48,905 --> 00:04:50,806
...and that will be the beginning...

72
00:04:50,874 --> 00:04:52,433
...of a brilliant career.

73
00:04:55,312 --> 00:04:56,940
Thank you, Professor Pitkannan.

74
00:05:01,451 --> 00:05:04,580
Do you think Helga is
a voluptuous Saint-Emilion...

75
00:05:04,988 --> 00:05:06,456
...or a buttery Chardonnay?

76
00:05:07,491 --> 00:05:10,290
You mean, Helga with the coils.
Works over at Kinko Copy?

77
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:12,124
That's her. What do you think.

78
00:05:12,195 --> 00:05:13,595
What do I think?

79
00:05:14,331 --> 00:05:15,321
Bud Light.

80
00:05:16,366 --> 00:05:17,698
That's not funny.

81
00:05:19,769 --> 00:05:22,739
I'd appreciate it if you wouldn't
demoralize my crew.

82
00:05:22,806 --> 00:05:24,968
Face it, you're just not a leader of men.

83
00:05:25,041 --> 00:05:26,907
- Very funny.
- Then be a model.

84
00:05:28,712 --> 00:05:30,305
- How'd it go?
- How'd what go.

85
00:05:31,314 --> 00:05:33,613
The big meeting
with the god of your idolatry.

86
00:05:33,683 --> 00:05:34,946
With Pitkannan?

87
00:05:35,385 --> 00:05:36,751
It went great.

88
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:38,079
Rah.

89
00:05:38,355 --> 00:05:39,823
Can't you stay?

90
00:05:39,890 --> 00:05:41,449
The best never rest.

91
00:05:41,958 --> 00:05:44,120
- I hate him.
- He is a tad compulsive.

92
00:05:44,194 --> 00:05:46,425
He has to be.
Harvard's not his inheritance.

93
00:05:46,496 --> 00:05:47,623
It's true.

94
00:05:47,797 --> 00:05:49,959
Harvard doesn't have any standards left.

95
00:05:50,033 --> 00:05:51,797
They let in anyone who's bright.

96
00:05:52,068 --> 00:05:53,559
I'm worried about him.

97
00:05:54,738 --> 00:05:56,764
Poor guy's the pet of a Nobel Laureate.

98
00:05:56,840 --> 00:05:59,639
Pitkannan spends more time
on Nightline than in lecture.

99
00:05:59,709 --> 00:06:01,507
He's a celebrity, not an intellectual.

100
00:06:01,578 --> 00:06:04,912
He'll still get Monty into graduate school
and set him up for life.

101
00:06:05,048 --> 00:06:06,107
For life.

102
00:06:06,182 --> 00:06:07,741
Sounds like a death sentence.

103
00:06:23,733 --> 00:06:25,065
What the hell was that?

104
00:06:54,030 --> 00:06:55,464
Your hard drive is fried.

105
00:06:58,134 --> 00:06:59,602
I got ten chapters printed.

106
00:06:59,669 --> 00:07:01,433
You've done ten chapters already?

107
00:07:01,671 --> 00:07:03,401
I'm going to get Xeroxes.

108
00:07:03,473 --> 00:07:05,840
- Wait until morning.
- It's my only copy.

109
00:07:05,909 --> 00:07:08,003
Are you afraid someone will steal it?

110
00:07:08,078 --> 00:07:10,138
I can't take any chances. This is my life.

111
00:07:10,213 --> 00:07:13,149
I know you worked really hard,
but it's not your life, Monty.

112
00:07:14,351 --> 00:07:15,842
- I'm going with him!
- Good!

113
00:07:41,244 --> 00:07:42,576
Monty, wait up!

114
00:07:42,946 --> 00:07:44,676
I didn't ask you to tag along.

115
00:07:45,382 --> 00:07:47,010
You're welcome, you bastard!

116
00:07:47,317 --> 00:07:49,548
Face it, Courtney,
you can't keep up with me.

117
00:07:55,191 --> 00:07:57,183
Monty, are you okay?

118
00:07:59,529 --> 00:08:00,861

What're you doing?

119
00:08:02,132 --> 00:08:03,896
God. It's down there.

120
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:05,668
In the boiler room?

121
00:08:05,769 --> 00:08:07,203
I got to get into Widener.

122
00:08:07,270 --> 00:08:09,501
Widener is closed. Wait till the morning.

123
00:08:09,572 --> 00:08:11,131
I can't wait till morning!

124
00:08:11,775 --> 00:08:12,765
You're hurt.

125
00:08:15,478 --> 00:08:17,470
Would you like my help getting in?

126
00:08:22,452 --> 00:08:24,011
Since you asked so nicely....

127
00:08:24,888 --> 00:08:25,981
Come on.

128
00:08:27,657 --> 00:08:31,185
- Through the front door?
- Yes, through the front. I know the guard.

129
00:08:34,764 --> 00:08:35,754
Hi, Chuck.

130
00:08:35,832 --> 00:08:38,461
Courtney. It's kind of late. You okay?

131
00:08:39,035 --> 00:08:42,597
Yeah. I was here earlier
and I think I misplaced my wallet.

132
00:08:42,672 --> 00:08:44,698
I was wondering if anyone turned it in?

133
00:08:45,575 --> 00:08:48,409
I don't remember
anybody bringing in a wallet but...

134
00:08:48,645 --> 00:08:50,170
...let me take a look.

135
00:08:52,048 --> 00:08:53,949
I found a hat here and...

136
00:08:54,751 --> 00:08:55,946
...a scarf...

137
00:08:56,186 --> 00:08:57,745
...and a banana.

138
00:08:58,388 --> 00:09:00,186
What color was that wallet?

139
00:09:00,523 --> 00:09:02,515
It was green. Alligator green.

140
00:09:02,592 --> 00:09:04,959
Alligator green. That's kind of spiffy.

141
00:10:32,248 --> 00:10:33,307
Don't!

142
00:10:38,788 --> 00:10:39,881
Calm down!

143
00:10:43,426 --> 00:10:44,519
It's mine!

144
00:10:45,128 --> 00:10:46,994
That's all I want. It's important.

145
00:10:47,063 --> 00:10:48,258
It belongs to me.

146
00:10:48,331 --> 00:10:50,800
Finders keepers, losers weepers.

147
00:10:51,367 --> 00:10:53,996
Don't you knock before coming
into someone's home?

148
00:10:54,070 --> 00:10:56,596
- It's not worth anything.
- Why do you want it then?

149
00:10:57,473 --> 00:10:58,270
How much?

150
00:10:58,341 --> 00:11:00,310
- How much?
- Yeah, how much?

151
00:11:00,443 --> 00:11:02,605
- Got a check.
- Is it a certified check.

152
00:11:02,679 --> 00:11:05,114
How about a six-month CD?
You got one of those.

153
00:11:05,515 --> 00:11:07,040
I need something I can chew.

154
00:11:07,116 --> 00:11:08,550
Okay. You want food?

155
00:11:09,018 --> 00:11:11,453
I'll bring you some. Then you give me that.

156
00:11:12,789 --> 00:11:14,519
What size underpants you wear?

157
00:11:15,158 --> 00:11:16,057
Excuse me?

158
00:11:16,259 --> 00:11:18,660
I could use a new pair of underpants.

159
00:11:18,728 --> 00:11:21,698
I'll bring you underpants.
Just don't burn any more pages.

160
00:11:21,764 --> 00:11:24,598
I'll bring you underpants
and you'll give me my thesis.

161
00:11:24,667 --> 00:11:25,691
Your thesis?

162
00:11:26,736 --> 00:11:29,262
Is that what this piece of shit's
supposed to be?

163
00:11:29,606 --> 00:11:32,235
- What's it supposed to be on, Harvard?
- Government.

164
00:11:32,475 --> 00:11:33,374
Government.

165
00:11:33,443 --> 00:11:36,242
I didn't recognize you! You're Dan Quayle!

166
00:11:36,379 --> 00:11:38,780
You came back to finish your education.

167
00:11:39,782 --> 00:11:42,911
Okay, Harvard. You study government,
so this should be easy.

168
00:11:42,986 --> 00:11:45,251
You want something, I need something.

169
00:11:45,655 --> 00:11:47,317
Go get me a glazed doughnut.

170
00:11:47,891 --> 00:11:48,984
A glazed doughnut?

171
00:11:49,058 --> 00:11:51,220
Make sure the glaze is not all broke.

172
00:11:51,561 --> 00:11:52,859
And your underpants?

173
00:11:52,929 --> 00:11:54,488
What about my underpants?

174
00:11:55,798 --> 00:11:57,858
Clean underpants too! That's right!

175
00:11:57,934 --> 00:12:00,403
- Great. Glazed doughnut--
- Pristine, glazed doughnut.

176
00:12:00,470 --> 00:12:03,372
Pristine, glazed doughnut
and underpants. Okay?

177
00:12:03,539 --> 00:12:04,700
What do I get?

178
00:12:04,974 --> 00:12:08,069
Well, for each thing you get,
I'll give you one page.

179
00:12:08,912 --> 00:12:10,210
- A chapter?
- No.

180
00:12:10,313 --> 00:12:11,906
A page is a thing!

181
00:12:11,981 --> 00:12:13,950
A chapter is a whole lot of things.

182
00:12:14,350 --> 00:12:16,649
There are 88 pages in that thesis.

183
00:12:17,186 --> 00:12:19,417
There are 83 pages now.

184
00:12:23,993 --> 00:12:27,020
Looks I like I found a way to live
through the winter, Harvard.

185
00:12:36,372 --> 00:12:39,706
I hope you got it. I just went through
two years of Lost and Found.

186
00:12:42,211 --> 00:12:43,577
You didn't get it.

187
00:12:45,481 --> 00:12:48,349
All right, all right.
Let's get you to the infirmary.

188
00:12:51,287 --> 00:12:52,277
Perfect.

189
00:12:53,156 --> 00:12:54,715
Glaze is almost perfect.

190
00:12:54,824 --> 00:12:56,190
There's no point.

191
00:12:56,259 --> 00:12:57,921
- Who are you calling?
- University cops.

192
00:12:57,994 --> 00:13:00,054
No, let's negotiate.
How much cash do we have?

193
00:13:00,129 --> 00:13:01,119
He can't eat money.

194
00:13:01,197 --> 00:13:02,597
Doesn't money buy food?

195
00:13:02,699 --> 00:13:04,827
Helga, you're brilliant!

196
00:13:04,901 --> 00:13:05,766
I love you.

197
00:13:05,835 --> 00:13:07,326
He's probably schizophrenic.

198
00:13:07,403 --> 00:13:09,872
Most homeless are schizophrenics.

199
00:13:09,939 --> 00:13:10,838
I have $50.

200
00:13:10,907 --> 00:13:12,705
I can't pay you back soon.

201
00:13:12,775 --> 00:13:14,641
I'll call my esteemed father.

202
00:13:14,744 --> 00:13:17,646
If I can convince him
the money's not for me, maybe I...

203
00:13:17,714 --> 00:13:19,239
You don't understand.

204
00:13:19,315 --> 00:13:23,218
This guy could be using my thesis
for toilet paper, or eating it.

205
00:13:23,820 --> 00:13:27,313
He has no respect for himself,
much less for what I'm struggling to do.

206
00:13:27,390 --> 00:13:30,258
He liked tormenting me.
You should've seen the look on his face.

207
00:13:30,326 --> 00:13:31,624
He wants me to fail.

208
00:13:31,694 --> 00:13:34,027
Pitkannan advised Rapp's thesis last year.

209
00:13:34,097 --> 00:13:37,067
He dropped him because
he didn't have a rough draft.

210
00:13:37,133 --> 00:13:38,192
Oh, God!

211
00:13:38,901 --> 00:13:41,735
You need rest. We'll get a fresh doughnut
in the morning.

212
00:13:41,804 --> 00:13:43,033
I won't wait on this--

213
00:13:43,106 --> 00:13:45,405
He doesn't know you.
I'm sure he doesn't want you to fail.

214
00:13:45,475 --> 00:13:47,000
Just reason with him.

215
00:13:47,677 --> 00:13:49,805
Just deal with him like a human being.

216
00:13:49,879 --> 00:13:52,474
I know he's a human being. I smelled him.

217
00:13:52,682 --> 00:13:56,175
He's a worthless, stinky, filthy,
useless human being.

218
00:13:56,285 --> 00:13:57,776
Hello, Security?

219
00:14:01,457 --> 00:14:02,823
Watch your step.

220
00:14:06,095 --> 00:14:07,859
You bunch of scavengers!

221
00:14:07,997 --> 00:14:10,557
Thanks for the doughnut, you little stoolie!

222
00:14:11,134 --> 00:14:12,158
Come on.

223
00:14:13,136 --> 00:14:14,661
Hey, Monty, is that him?

224
00:14:15,138 --> 00:14:16,629
He's a little old man.

225
00:14:17,140 --> 00:14:19,803
Officer, it isn't here! Now, where is it?

226
00:14:19,876 --> 00:14:22,209
It's not down there and it's not on him.

227
00:14:27,316 --> 00:14:29,979
You have violated
Cambridge city ordinances...

228
00:14:30,053 --> 00:14:33,217
...and are charged with public intoxication
and/or vagrancy...

229
00:14:33,289 --> 00:14:35,724
...and/or panhandling. If you plead guilty...

230
00:14:35,792 --> 00:14:37,021
...please sit down.

231
00:14:37,093 --> 00:14:39,358
If you plead not guilty, take a step forward.

232
00:14:42,532 --> 00:14:43,522
Name?

233
00:14:43,766 --> 00:14:45,257
Simon B. Wilder, Judge.

234
00:14:45,535 --> 00:14:48,130
As a taxpayer, I'd like to request
a trial by jury.

235
00:14:48,771 --> 00:14:51,297
And when was the last time
you paid taxes?

236
00:14:51,541 --> 00:14:53,203
Three times this last week.

237
00:14:53,276 --> 00:14:55,541
- You paid taxes three times?
- Yes, sir.

238
00:14:55,878 --> 00:14:58,541
There's a federal, state
and county tax on wine.

239
00:15:01,651 --> 00:15:02,710
Mr. Wilder...

240
00:15:02,785 --> 00:15:05,949
...the court concedes
you have paid various taxes...

241
00:15:06,556 --> 00:15:08,957

...nevertheless a jury trial is not called for.

242
00:15:09,325 --> 00:15:12,784
Charges of public drunkenness,
trespassing and vagrancy stand.

243
00:15:13,129 --> 00:15:15,098
- How do you plead?
- Not guilty.

244
00:15:16,165 --> 00:15:20,261
You were found living in a furnace room
under Harvard's Widener Library.

245
00:15:20,603 --> 00:15:24,062
With all due respect, sir,
Harvard University is a land-grant school.

246
00:15:24,941 --> 00:15:27,775
Constitutionally,
I was living on public grounds.

247
00:15:27,844 --> 00:15:29,540
I'll drop the trespassing charge...

248
00:15:29,612 --> 00:15:32,514
...but you tested as being drunk
at the time of your arrest.

249
00:15:32,849 --> 00:15:35,944
At the time of my arrest,
I was neither driving an automobile...

250
00:15:36,018 --> 00:15:39,250
...or operating heavy farm equipment.
I was sitting alone, reading.

251
00:15:39,322 --> 00:15:40,813
I'm well past drinking age.

252
00:15:40,957 --> 00:15:44,758
If I take a little drink to kill the winter chill,
it's certainly not a crime.

253
00:15:44,827 --> 00:15:49,265
If it were, every fan at a Harvard-Yale
football game would be behind bars. Come on!

254
00:15:52,735 --> 00:15:54,363
Be careful, Mr. Wilder.

255
00:15:54,670 --> 00:15:57,367
You're coming dangerously close
to contempt of court.

